result.execSummary:
The defendant Aaron L. Bouzek was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 1st Degree Child Sexual Assault - Intercourse with Person under 12 [Modifiers: Mandatory minimum 948.02(1)(b) or multiple acts], a class B felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.02(1)(b).
  • 1st Degree Child Sexual Assault - Intercourse with Person under 12 [Modifiers: Mandatory minimum 948.02(1)(b) or multiple acts], a class B felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.02(1)(b).
  • 1st Degree Child Sexual Assault - Intercourse with Person under 12 [Modifiers: Mandatory minimum 948.02(1)(b) or multiple acts], a class B felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.02(1)(b).
  • 1st Degree Child Sexual Assault - Intercourse with Person under 12 [Modifiers: Mandatory minimum 948.02(1)(b) or multiple acts], a class B felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.02(1)(b).
  • Possession of Child Pornography, a class D felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.12(1m).
  • Child Sexual Exploitation - Videos, Records, etc., a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.05(1)(b).
  • 1st Degree Child Sex Assault - Sexual Contact with Person under Age of 13, a class B felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.02(1)(e).
  • Child Sexual Exploitation - Videos, Records, etc., a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.05(1)(b).
  • Child Sexual Exploitation - Videos, Records, etc., a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.05(1)(b).
  • Possession of Child Pornography, a class D felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.12(1m).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample. 
Defendant shall not have any contact with the victim S.B or any other victims or their families while serving his sentence or on extended supervision.
Defendant shall pay restitution to the victim and a 10% restitution surcharge.
